      <procstep>
        <procdesc>The raster-based, false-color composite of the DVRFS region was derived from Landsat 5 Thematic Mapper (TM) data collected April 5, 14, and 28, 1996. The image is a composite of spectral bands 2, 4, and 7 in RGB (Red-Green-Blue) space. The image was further variably processed in hue-saturation-intensity space to emphasize specific features useful for identifying and mapping surficial deposits, such as desert varnish, pavement development, and various compositional components in surficial deposits (e.g., carbonate, sodium salts, feldspar), in order to produce pseudo-color images that approximate and locally enhance the appearance of natural-color aerial photographs.  Individual Landsat scenes were hand-registered and clipped or mosaiced to match the 21 U.S. Geological Survey 1:100,000-scale topographic quadrangle boundaries covered by the DVRFS. The quadrangle images were subsequently compiled into one image and compressed using LizardTech MrSID software to reduce the file size.
		
Data are available from USGS/EROS, Sioux Falls, SD. Questions concerning the use or redistribution of USGS/EROS data should be directed to: 
		
USGS/EROS Customer Services 
Mundt Federal Building 
Sioux Falls, SD 57198 
Toll Free: 800-252-4547 
Telephone: 605-594-6151 
Facsimile: 605-594-6589 
Email: custserv@usgs.gov</procdesc>
        <procdate>1999</procdate>
      </procstep>
